\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
When Aggregation Misleads: Bias in Small Area Estimates of Poverty with
 Aggregate Data
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Paul Corral Rodas
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The World Bank Group - Poverty and Equity Global Practice (pcorralrodas@worldban
k.org).
 The author acknowledges financial support from the World Bank.
 Special thanks to Carlos Rodriguez-Castelan, Alexandru Cojocaru, Tara Vishwanat
h, and Isabel Molina for comments on an earlier draft.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
This paper explores why small area poverty estimates from models at the
 household level, but that only use aggregate data as covariates, exhibit
 systematic bias.
 The analysis demonstrates that this bias stems from the models' inability
 to fully capture between-household variation in welfare, as they rely solely
 on covariates aggregated at geographic levels.
 Through model-based simulations, I show that the bias in these models is
 minimized when the empirical variability of simulated welfare based on
 the model is closest to the true empirical variance of welfare at the area
 level.
 The finding also has implications for bias in unit-level models.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
\begin_inset VSpace vfill
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Key words:
\series default
 Small area estimation; poverty mapping; satellite imagery
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
JEL classification: 
\series default
C13; C55; C87; C15
\begin_inset Newpage pagebreak
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Household surveys aimed at gauging a population's living standards often
 lack representativeness beyond broad regions or specific population demographic
s.
 Additionally, there is a risk that many pertinent locations or groups may
 be omitted from these surveys.
 However, detailed information on poverty is crucial for effectively targeting
 resources to alleviate it.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The demand for disaggregated statistics has increased the reliance on indirect
 techniques that integrate supplementary data from censuses, registries,
 or larger-scale surveys.
 These methods are used to produce sufficiently precise statistics for granular
 populations.
 Small area estimation encompasses a broad range of statistical techniques
 designed to enhance the precision of estimates when household surveys lack
 the sample size required for the desired level of accuracy.
 Among these techniques, model-based approaches stand out by leveraging
 the concept of "borrowing strength" from larger datasets or auxiliary informati
on.
 These methods use models that establish relationships across areas (e.g.,
 regression techniques), enabling the creation of indirect estimators (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealt
key "molina2010small"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Most model-based techniques fall into two main categories: unit-level models
 and area-level models.
 Unit-level models are generally applied when data on individual units (e.g.,
 households) are available, while area-level models are used when only aggregate
 data for specific geographic areas (e.g., area means) are accessible, as
 described by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "fay1979estimates"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 In poverty estimation, unit-level models predict the welfare distribution
 first and then apply a threshold to determine the proportion of people
 below that threshold.
 In contrast, area-level models directly estimate the poverty rate for an
 area.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Unit-level models face limitations when survey and census data are from
 different years — a common issue in developing countries where censuses
 and surveys are conducted infrequently.
 Area-level models, however, provide a feasible alternative.
 These models rely on linear functional forms and perform estimation and
 prediction using only aggregate data for geographic entities of interest
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "fay1979estimates"
literal "false"

\end_inset

; 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "torabi2014small"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 Another approach, unit-context models, employs an estimation stage where
 household-level measures are modeled as a linear function of area-level
 characteristics (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "nguyen2012method,lange2018small,masaki2020small"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 Unit-context, like unit-level models predict the welfare distribution first
 and then apply a threshold to determine the proportion of people below
 that threshold, but do so only using area-level characteristics.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Although alluring, unit-context models, have been discouraged due to the
 method resulting in biased estimates.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeauthor
key "corral2022guidelines"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 (2022) show that the method is unable to fully replicate the welfare distributi
on which results in biased estimates.
 For a practical example of the resulting bias, see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "edochie2024small"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 In that work the authors present the aggregated estimates at the geographic
 level of representativeness and it is evident that across many areas the
 differences to direct estimates are considerable (see Figures 7 to 9).
 Moreover, it can be seen that the majority of the estimates fall above
 the 45 degree line, suggesting an upward bias in the estimates.
 Using real world data, where samples are taken following methods implemented
 in developing countries, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "corral2023poverty"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 present evidence on how unit-context models produce biased estimates of
 poverty and that the noise and bias of unit-context models is considerably
 larger than that produced by area-level models.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A key question is what is the source of the bias in unit-context models.
 In this note, the simulations implemented by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeauthor
key "corral2022guidelines"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 (2022) are used to study the source of the method's bias.
 The bias studied here, goes beyond the potential bias of the method noted
 in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeauthor
key "rodas2021pull"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 (2021) which was related to a sampling issue.
 Instead, the bias noted in this paper, is related to the transformation
 bias noted by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "wurz2022estimating"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 These authors attempt to address the same issue as 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "nguyen2012method"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "lange2018small"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "masaki2020small"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 of not having auxiliary microdata and relying on aggregate population-level
 auxiliary information.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "wurz2022estimating"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 note that relying on aggregate level data to model household-level welfare
 leads to first-order bias from back-transformation and second-order bias
 from using aggregate data.
 They note that using aggregate means as covariates instead of individual
 values introduces additional bias due to the convexity of the back-transformati
on function.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The bias studied here is related to the poor model explanatory power of
 unit-context models and is related to the bias noted by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "wurz2022estimating"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Because unit-context methods model transformed household-level welfare
 as a linear function of area-level covariates only, these are unable to
 adequately account for between household variations in welfare.
 The simulations undertaken here show that areas where the variance of predicted
 welfare is aligned to the area's true variance of welfare are those that
 exhibit the lowest bias across the entire welfare distribution.
 This illustrates that under unit-level and unit-context models bias at
 the area level is a function of the dependent variable's mean and the empirical
 variance of the linear fit.
 The dependent variable benefits from the use of EB methods but the empirical
 variance is fully dependent on the auxiliary data at hand and how aligned
 it is to the population.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The note proceeds to present the assumed model for unit-level small area
 estimation and provides a discussion on why not accounting for variance
 leads to biased estimates of poverty.
 The method for creating simulated data is illustrated, followed by the
 results.
 Finally, conclusions are presented.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Small area estimation 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec: method"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The model based small area estimation methods described in this paper are
 dependent on an assumed model.
 The nested error model used for small area was originally proposed by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "battese1988asa"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 to produce county-level corn and soybean crop area estimates for the American
 state of Iowa.
 For the estimation of poverty and welfare, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "molina2010small"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "elbers2003micro"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 assume that the transformed welfare 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{ah}$
\end_inset

 for each household 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 within each location 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 in the population is linearly related to a 
\begin_inset Formula $1\times K$
\end_inset

 vector of characteristics (or correlates) 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{ah}$
\end_inset

 for that household, according to the nested error model:
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
For simplicity 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{ah}$
\end_inset

is considered the transformed welfare.
 The most common transformation applied is the natural logarithm.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y_{ah}=x_{ah}\beta+\eta_{a}+e_{ah},\:h=1,\ldots,N_{a},\,a=1,\ldots,A,\label{eq:1-1-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{ah}$
\end_inset

 are respectively location and household-specific idiosyncratic errors,
 assumed to be independent from each other, following: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\eta_{a}\stackrel{iid}{\sim}N\left(0,\sigma_{\eta}^{2}\right),\:e_{ah}\stackrel{iid}{\sim}N\left(0,\sigma_{e}^{2}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where the variances 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{\eta}^{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{e}^{2}$
\end_inset

 are unknown.
 Here, 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is the number of locations in which the population is divided and 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{a}$
\end_inset

 is the number of households in location 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

, for 
\begin_inset Formula $a=1,\ldots,A$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{a}$
\end_inset

 is the sample size from area 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

.
 Finally, 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Formula $K\times1$
\end_inset

 vector of regression coefficients.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One of the main assumptions is that errors are normally distributed.
 The assumption implies that, conditional on the observed characteristics,
 the model's errors are normally distributed.
 To obtain estimates, the first step is to fit the model from Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:1-1-1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 to the observed sample data via any method providing consistent estimators.
 Usual fitting methods under this approach are maximum likelihood (ML) or
 restricted maximum likelihood (REML), both based on the normal likelihood,
 and H3 method, which does not specify a distribution.
 This yields the vector of parameter estimates: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\hat{\theta}=\left(\hat{\beta},\hat{\sigma}_{\eta}^{2},\hat{\sigma}_{e}^{2}\right).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The empirical best (EB) area effects for the model are estimated from:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\hat{\gamma}_{a}\left(\bar{y}_{a}-\bar{x}_{a}\hat{\beta}\right),\quad\hat{\gamma}_{a}=\frac{\hat{\sigma}_{\eta}^{2}}{\hat{\sigma}_{\eta}^{2}+\hat{\sigma}_{e}^{2}/n_{a}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{x}_{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{y}_{a}$
\end_inset

 are the sample means in area 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

, respectively.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The variance for the area effects are given by (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "molina2010small"
literal "false"

\end_inset

):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{var}\left[\eta_{a}|\bar{y}_{a}\right]=\sigma_{\eta}^{2}(1-\gamma_{a})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Making use of the parameters estimated from the model of Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:1-1-1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, it is possible to produce a value of 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{ah}$
\end_inset

for every household in the census data:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
y_{ah}^{*}=x_{ah}\hat{\beta}+\hat{\gamma}_{a}\left(\bar{y}_{a}-\bar{x}_{a}\hat{\beta}\right)+\varepsilon_{ah}^{*}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon$
\end_inset

 is drawn from 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{ah}^{*}\sim N(0,\sigma_{\eta}^{2}(1-\gamma_{a})+σ_{e}^{2})$
\end_inset

.
 This Monte Carlo procedure is often repeated 100 times in ordet to derive
 indicators under each simulated population and then average across to derive
 the final EB estimate.
 Notice how in the simulated vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{ah}\hat{\beta}+\hat{\gamma}_{a}\left(\bar{y}_{a}-\bar{x}_{a}\hat{\beta}\right)$
\end_inset

 does not vary across simulations, only 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{ah}^{*}$
\end_inset

 vary across the simulated vectors.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Alternatively, because we assume normally distributed errors, the probability
 of being poor for any household 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 in area 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is entirely dependent on its expected welfare, 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{h}\hat{β},$
\end_inset

 its idiosyncratic error, 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{e}_{h}$
\end_inset

, and the predicted area effect 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\gamma}_{a}\left(\bar{y}_{a}-\bar{x}_{a}\hat{\beta}\right)$
\end_inset

 which are assumed to follow 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{h}\sim N(0,σ_{e}^{2})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{a}\sim N\left(\gamma_{a}\left(\bar{y}_{a}-\bar{x}_{a}\beta\right),\sigma_{\eta}^{2}(1-\gamma_{a})\right)$
\end_inset

, respectively.
 The empirical best estimated probability of a household being poor is given
 by:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Prob\:poor_{ha}=Φ\,\left(\frac{z-\hat{y}_{ah}}{\sqrt{\hat{\sigma}_{\eta}^{2}(1-\hat{\gamma}_{a})+\hat{σ}{}_{e}^{2}}}\right)\label{eq:cum prob}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 is the transformed poverty threshold and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{y}_{ah}=x_{ah}\hat{\beta}+\hat{\gamma}_{a}\left(\bar{y}_{a}-\bar{x}_{a}\hat{\beta}_{0}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 The poverty rate for the area is given by the average probability of being
 poor across households.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Traditionally, this process is approximated via Monte Carlo simulations
 as noted above.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Within a given area, the only thing that varies across households are the
 covariates.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Under the assumed model, variation in simulated welfare across the population
 (
\begin_inset Formula $S_{y_{a}}^{2*}$
\end_inset

) in a given area is the sum of two components: 1) the variability of the
 explained portion, 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{\hat{y}_{a}}^{2*}=\frac{1}{N_{a}}\sum_{h}\left(\hat{y}_{ah}-\bar{y}_{a}^{*}\right)^{2}$
\end_inset

 , and 2) variability in the simulated errors 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{N_{a}}\sum_{h}\left(\varepsilon_{ah}^{*2}\right)$
\end_inset

: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{array}{cc}
S_{y_{a}}^{2*}= & \frac{1}{N_{a}}\sum_{h}\left(y_{ah}^{*}-\bar{y}_{a}^{*}\right)^{2}\\
S_{y_{a}}^{2*}= & \frac{1}{N_{a}}\sum_{h}(\hat{y}_{ah}+\varepsilon_{ah}^{*}-\bar{y}_{a}^{*})^{2}\\
S_{y_{a}}^{2*}= & \frac{1}{N_{a}}\sum_{h}\left(\hat{y}_{ah}^{2}+\varepsilon_{ah}^{*2}+\bar{y}_{a}^{2*}+2\hat{y}_{ah}\varepsilon_{ah}^{*}-2\hat{y}_{ah}\bar{y}_{a}^{*}-2\bar{y}_{a}^{*}\varepsilon_{ah}^{*}\right)\\
S_{y_{a}}^{2*}= & \frac{1}{N_{a}}\sum_{h}\left(\hat{y}_{ah}-\bar{y}_{a}^{*}\right)^{2}+\frac{1}{N_{a}}\sum_{h}\left(\varepsilon_{ah}^{*2}\right)
\end{array}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The bias of poverty estimates at the area level will be determined by difference
s between the true 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{y_{a}}^{2}$
\end_inset

 and the simulated 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{y_{a}}^{2*}$
\end_inset

.
 This is simplified if we assume that the dependent variable for a given
 area follows a log-normal distribution.
 Then the simulated poverty rate for a given area under a given threshold
 (
\begin_inset Formula $\ln z)$
\end_inset

 under the assumption is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
FGT_{0a}^{*}=\Phi\,\left(\frac{\ln z-\bar{y}_{a}}{\sqrt{S_{y_{a}}^{2*}}}\right)\label{eq:loglinear}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consequently, the poverty rate for a given area is a function of 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{y}_{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{y_{a}}^{2^{*}}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Unit-context models are an approximation to the assumed underlying data
 generating process from Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:1-1-1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 Originally introduced by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "nguyen2012method"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, and then re-introduced by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "lange2018small"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and modified by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "masaki2020small"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Unit-context models are defined as models where household-level welfare
 is modeled using only area and sub-area level characteristics.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "masaki2020small"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 suggest that the model should include characteristics that explain variability
 at a geographic level below the one for which we aim to estimate poverty.
 A possible unit-context model follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
y_{sach}=z_{sac}\alpha+t_{sa}\omega+g_{s}\lambda+\eta_{sa}+\varepsilon_{sach}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 is used for an aggregation level that is over the target areas (a super-area)
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 is used for subareas, e.g., clusters that are nested in area 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{sac}$
\end_inset

 contains subarea-level characteristics, 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{sa}$
\end_inset

 includes area-level characteristics and 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{s}$
\end_inset

 is composed of super-area-level characteristics (which may include super-area
 fixed effects).
 The regression coefficients across these levels are respectively denoted
 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha,$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

.
 The random effects, 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{sa}$
\end_inset

, are specified in this model at the area level, same as in Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:1-1-1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 Note that, among the set of covariates in this model, none is at the unit-level
; covariates only vary at the subarea-level and above.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Nevertheless, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "lange2018small"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "masaki2020small"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 undertake unrealistic validations where welfare is not dependent on unit-level
 characteristics leading to naive results.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A key feature of unit-context models is that the linear fit only explains
 a relatively small amount of the total variance of the dependent variable
 (
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

), with a coefficient of determination (
\begin_inset Formula $R^{2}$
\end_inset

) that is often quite lower than models that include household level covariates,
 and ranges between 0.15 to 0.25 in most instances.
 Define 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{y}$
\end_inset

 as the standard deviation of the sample's dependent variable, the coefficient
 of determination, 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{2},$
\end_inset

 is given by:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
R^{2}=1-\frac{\hat{\sigma}_{\eta}^{2}+\hat{σ}{}_{e}^{2}}{S_{y}^{2}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consequently, because unit-context models have lower explanatory power since
 they only rely on area-level covariates, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\sigma}_{\eta_{uc}}^{2}$
\end_inset

 is the unit-context model estimate of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{\eta}^{2}$
\end_inset

 , and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{σ}{}_{e_{uc}}^{2}$
\end_inset

 is the unit-context model estimate of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma{}_{e}^{2}$
\end_inset

, then:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
R_{uc}^{2}=1-\frac{\hat{\sigma}_{\eta_{uc}}^{2}+\hat{σ}{}_{e_{uc}}^{2}}{S_{y}^{2}}<R^{2}=1-\frac{\hat{\sigma}_{\eta}^{2}+\hat{σ}{}_{e}^{2}}{S_{y}^{2}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{\sigma}_{\eta_{uc}}^{2}+\hat{σ}{}_{e_{uc}}^{2}>\hat{\sigma}_{\eta}^{2}+\hat{σ}{}_{e}^{2}.\label{eq:var_uc}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The lower 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{2}$
\end_inset

 of unit-context models implies that the explained portion of welfare is
 lower than the true portion of explained welfare.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When simulating vectors of the dependent variable at the national level,
 the empirical standard deviation of the dependent variable is approximated
 under unit-level and unit-context models.
 However, under unit-context models the empirical standard deviation at
 the area level is not properly approximated due to the model misspecification.
 Consequently, when creating simulated vectors of welfare under unit context
 models the variation in simulated welfare across the population in an area
 (
\begin_inset Formula $S_{y_{a}}^{2*}$
\end_inset

) will not match that of the true population.
 From Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:var_uc"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, we know that:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{h}\left(\varepsilon_{ah_{uc}}^{*2}\right)>\sum_{h}\left(\varepsilon_{ah}^{*2}\right).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Additionally, given the poor model fit we also know that:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{h}\left(\hat{y}_{ah_{uc}}-\bar{y}_{a_{uc}}^{*}\right)^{2}<\sum_{h}\left(\hat{y}_{ah}-\bar{y}_{a}^{*}\right)^{2}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Hence, under unit-context models some areas will have a value of 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{y_{a}}^{2*}$
\end_inset

 that is larger than that of the true DGP and some will have a smaller or
 equal value of 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{y_{a}}^{2*}$
\end_inset

.
 This result, coupled with Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:loglinear"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 implies that the bias of unit-context models will be larger in areas where
 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{y_{a}}^{2*}$
\end_inset

 is most different from the true model's 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{y_{a}}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The focus here is the model's performance on estimating poverty.
 However, the poor model fit also affects predictions of welfare.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "corral2022guidelines"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 present evidence that unit-context models will do a good job at predicting
 the model's dependent variable (
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

), thanks to the use of empirical best predictors.
 A similar result is presented by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "chen2024effects"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 who indicate that under model misspecification, unit-context models will
 perform just as well as area level models in predicting the model's dependent
 variable.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Under unit-level and unit-context models welfare is usually transformed
 to ensure errors are normally distributed to conform to the model's assumptions.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Nevertheless, this seems to only hold true when estimating the mean of
 the dependent variable of the model is the goal.
 It does not hold true when the goal is estimating the original untransformed
 equivalized income or expenditure.
 Under unit-context models, bias is introduced when the goal is a measure
 that may be distributionally sensitive – e.g., poverty or equivalized income
 or expenditure.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "corral2022guidelines"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 present evidence from simulations on how unit-context models will produce
 biased predictions of the back transformed dependent variable, i.e.
 equivalized income or expenditure (see figure 5.3).
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "wurz2022estimating"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 also present evidence on how unit-context models will lead to biased estimates
 of welfare that arise from the back transformation of the dependent variable.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Under unit-level models welfare is usually transformed to ensure errors
 are normally distributed to conform to the model's assumptions.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assuming log linearity, the simulated nested error model (
\begin_inset Formula $y_{ah}^{*}=x_{ah}\hat{\beta}_{0}+\hat{\gamma}_{a}\left(\bar{y}_{a}-\bar{x}_{a}\hat{\beta}_{0}\right)+\varepsilon_{ah}^{*}$
\end_inset

) implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $\exp\left(y_{ah}^{*}\right)=\exp\left(\hat{y}_{ah}\right)\exp\left(\varepsilon_{ah}^{*}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{ah}^{*}\sim N(0,\sigma_{\eta}^{2}(1-\gamma_{a})+σ_{e}^{2})$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $E\left[\exp\left(\varepsilon_{ah}^{*}\right)\right]=\exp\left(0.5\left(\sigma_{\eta}^{2}(1-\gamma_{a})+σ_{e}^{2}\right)\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, at the area level welfare will be equal to:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(\frac{1}{N_{a}}\sum_{h=1}^{N_{a}}\exp\left(\hat{y}_{ah}\right)\right)\exp\left(0.5\left(\sigma_{\eta}^{2}(1-\gamma_{a})+σ_{e}^{2}\right)\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consequently, just like for poverty, the predicted welfare under unit-context
 models will be more biased the more different 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{y_{a}}^{2*}$
\end_inset

 is from the true model's 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{y_{a}}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
————————————————————————-
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Define 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{y_{a}}$
\end_inset

 as the empirical standard deviation of the dependent variable in area 
\begin_inset Formula $a.$
\end_inset

 A variation of the 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{2}$
\end_inset

 can be measured at the area level and is defined as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
R_{a}^{2}=1-\frac{\sigma_{\eta}^{2}(1-\gamma_{a})+\hat{σ}{}_{e}^{2}}{S_{y_{a}}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Welfare at the area level is simulated as 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Because using only area level covariates does not adequatly explain welfare
 at the household level, under unit-context models the variance in welfare
 that is not explained due to the exclusion of household-level covariates
 is captured in the estimates of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{\eta}^{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{e}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 The values 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
This leads to low values of 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{2}$
\end_inset

 as well as 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{a}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Additionally, the empirical variation of 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 is equal to the empirical variation of 
\begin_inset Formula $x\beta$
\end_inset

, the empirical variation of the 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
For simplicity assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{ah}=\eta_{a}+e_{ah}$
\end_inset

, consequently the maximum likelihood estimator of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{\mathrm{var}}\left[u_{ah}\right]$
\end_inset

 is given by (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealt
key "miller1999john"
literal "false"

\end_inset

):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{\mathrm{var}}\left[u_{ah}\right]=
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
At the national level the sum of total sum of squares (
\begin_inset Formula $TSS$
\end_inset

) is given by:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
TSS=\sum_{a}\sum_{ah}\left(y_{ah}-\bar{y}\right)^{2},
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{y}$
\end_inset

 is the national level sample mean of the dependent variable.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $TSS$
\end_inset

 is equal to, the sum of :
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
this leads to the variance of the linear fit, plus the estimates of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{\eta}^{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{e}^{2}$
\end_inset

 to be approximately equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{var\mathit{\left[y\right]}.}$
\end_inset

This is true for unit-context and unit-level models.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
At the area level, however, there will be differences and these will lead
 to bias.
 To see this, assume welfare for a given area follows a log-normal distribution.
 Also assume that the linear fit of Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:1-1-1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 is normally distributed.
 Then the poverty rate for a given area under these assumptions is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
FGT_{0a}=Φ\,\left(\frac{\ln z-\bar{x}\hat{\beta}-\hat{\eta}_{a}}{\sqrt{\mathrm{var}\mathit{\left[x_{h}\hat{\beta}\right]}+\hat{\sigma}_{\eta a}^{2}+\hat{\sigma}_{e}^{2}}}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Because the use of EB ensures that for every sampled area 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $E\left[x\hat{\beta}+\hat{\eta}_{a}\right]=E\left[y_{a}\right]$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Recall that 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{ha}$
\end_inset

 is the transformed welfare.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 then at the area level bias in poverty arises because:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathrm{var}\mathit{\left[x_{h}\hat{\beta}\right]}+\hat{\sigma}_{\eta a}^{2}+\hat{\sigma}_{e}^{2}\neq\mathrm{var\left[\mathit{y_{a}}\right]}.\label{eq:variance}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
And because the variance of the linear fit of unit-context models is smaller,
 unit-context models are more likely to yield biased estimates of poverty.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Under unit-context models the bias of predicted welfare arises from the
 same issue as the bias in poverty – mainly the fact that:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{\sigma}_{\eta a_{uc}}^{2}+\hat{\sigma}_{e_{uc}}^{2}>\hat{\sigma}_{\eta a}^{2}+\hat{\sigma}_{e}^{2}\label{eq:variance-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
where the subscript 
\begin_inset Formula $uc$
\end_inset

 is used to denote estimates from the unit-context model.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the following section I present a model-based simulation to illustrate
 how 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{y_{a}}^{2*}$
\end_inset

 is related to biased estimates at the area level.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Simulation data
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:data"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Data is generated for the simulations following the assumed model from Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:1-1-1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Data is simulated following the same approach as 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "corral2022guidelines"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The write-up here is also borrowed from 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "corral2022guidelines"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The population size for the simulated data is 
\begin_inset Formula $N=500,000$
\end_inset

, and the observations are allocated among 
\begin_inset Formula $A=100$
\end_inset

 areas 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(a=1,\ldots,A\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Within each area 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

, observations are uniformly allocated over 
\begin_inset Formula $c=20$
\end_inset

 clusters 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(c_{a}=1,\ldots,C_{a}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Each cluster 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 consists of 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{ac}=250$
\end_inset

 observations.
 In this simulation experiment, a simple random sample of 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{ac}=10$
\end_inset

 households per cluster is taken, and this sample is kept fixed across simulatio
ns.
 Using a sample, it is possible to compare with estimators based on FH model
 (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "corral2022guidelines,molina2022estimation,rao2015small,fay1979estimates"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 The model that generates the population data contains both cluster and
 area effects.
 Cluster effects are simulated as 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{ac}\stackrel{iid}{\sim}N\left(0,0.1\right)$
\end_inset

, area effects as 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{a}\stackrel{iid}{\sim}N\left(0,0.15^{2}\right)$
\end_inset

 and household specific residuals as 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{ach}\overset{iid}{{\sim}}N\left(0,0.5^{2}\right)$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $h=1,\ldots,N_{ac}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $c=1,\ldots,C_{a}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $a=1,\ldots,A$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}$
\end_inset

 is a binary variable, taking value 1 when a random uniform number between
 0 and 1, at the household-level, is less than or equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $0.3+0.5\frac{a}{40}+0.2\frac{c}{10}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}$
\end_inset

 is a binary variable, taking value 1 when a random uniform number between
 0 and 1, at the household-level, is less than or equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $0.2$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $x_{3}$
\end_inset

 is a binary variable, taking value 1 when a random uniform number between
 0 and 1, at the household-level, is less than or equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $0.1+0.2\frac{a}{40}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $x_{4}$
\end_inset

 is a binary variable, taking value 1 when a random uniform number between
 0 and 1, at the household-level, is less than or equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $0.5+0.3\frac{a}{40}+0.1\frac{c}{10}$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $x_{5}$
\end_inset

 is a discrete variable, simulated as the rounded integer value of the maximum
 between 1 and a random Poisson variable with mean 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=3\left(1-0.1\frac{a}{40}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $x_{6}$
\end_inset

 is a binary variable, taking value 1 when a random uniform value between
 0 and 1 is less than or equal to 0.4.
 Note that the values of 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{6}$
\end_inset

 are not related to the area's label.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $x_{7}$
\end_inset

 is generated from a random Poisson variable with mean 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=3\left(\frac{c}{20}-\frac{a}{100}+u\right)$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 is a random uniform value between 0 and 1.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the unit-context model variations implemented here the PSU level mean
 of each covariate is used as the eligible covariates to fit the model.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this experiment, I take a grid of 99 poverty thresholds, corresponding
 to the 99 percentiles of the very first population generated.
 In total, 1,000 populations are generated.
 In each of the 1,000 populations, the following quantities are computed
 in every area for each of the 99 poverty lines: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
True poverty indicators 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{a}$
\end_inset

, using the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

census
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
CensusEB estimators 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\tau}_{a}^{CEB_{a}}$
\end_inset

 presented in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "rodas2021pull"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, based on a nested-error model with only 
\series bold
area
\series default
 random effects and including the unit-level values of the covariates.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{2}$
\end_inset

 for this model is roughly 0.60.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Unit-context CensusEB estimators 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\tau}_{a}^{UC-CEB_{a}}$
\end_inset

 based on a nested-error model with random effects at the 
\series bold
area-level
\series default
.
 This estimator follows the approach of Masaki et al.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeyearpar
key "masaki2020small"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{2}$
\end_inset

 of the resulting model hovers around 0.17.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The average difference between the true poverty indicator and the estimate
 across the 1,000 simulations represent the empirical bias for each area.
 
\end_layout

