\begin_layout Standard
As argued in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec: method"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, the bias arises because at the area level, the unit-context model does
 a poor job at capturing the empirical variation of the explained portion
 of the data, 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{\hat{y}}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
At the area level this is equal to: 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{N_{a}}\sum_{h}\left(\hat{y}_{ah}-\bar{y}_{a}^{*}\right)^{2}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

 Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:var"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 presents the value for 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{\hat{y}}^{2}$
\end_inset

 across areas.
 The true empirical variation of the explained portion, 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{\hat{y}}^{2}$
\end_inset

,ranges from 0.37 for the area with the lowest empirical variation to 0.86
 to the area with the largest, a similar range to the EB model.
 However, the range for the unit-context model is much smaller, from 0.07
 to 0.1.
 Nevertheless, on average, the total empirical variation of the dependent
 variable, 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{y}^{2}$
\end_inset

, is matched by unit-context models (Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:var2"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

; mean).
 This is because the model is fit at the national level and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{\eta}^{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{\eta}^{2}$
\end_inset

 are estimated to be much larger since the covariates capture so little
 of the total empirical variance of the dependent variable, 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{y}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Consequently, the range for the total empirical variance of the areas is
 minimal, from 0.813 to 0.844, compared to the truth of 0.632 to 1.119.
 Thus, in the unit-context models the larger estimates for 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{\eta}^{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{\eta}^{2}$
\end_inset

 only works at the national level, across areas this leads to some areas
 where 
\size small

\begin_inset Formula $S_{y_{a}}^{2*}$
\end_inset

 is
\size default
 considerably larger than the true 
\size small

\begin_inset Formula $S_{y_{a}}^{2}$
\end_inset


\size default
 and some where 
\size small

\begin_inset Formula $S_{y_{a}}^{2*}$
\end_inset


\size default
 is considerably smaller than the true 
\size small

\begin_inset Formula $S_{y_{a}}^{2}$
\end_inset


\size default
.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Unit-context models are biased because these deviate from the truth by assuming
 welfare is not dependent on unit level characteristics, which leads to
 poor fitting models.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:bias-1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 illustrates how this is manifested across select poverty lines.
 The absolute bias for a given area decrease as the ratio of model explained
 variance to true variance for a given area gets close to 1.
 Therefore, even if the use of empirical best methods guarantees that the
 mean of the dependent variable of the model at the area level is unbiased,
 because poverty is distribution dependent, the inability of unit-context
 models to approximate the full distribution at the area level leads to
 biased poverty estimates.
 
\end_layout

