\begin_layout Standard
A similar issue is observed for welfare (
\begin_inset Formula $\exp\left(y_{ah}^{*}\right)$
\end_inset

) under unit-context models.
 The absolute bias decreases as 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{y_{a}}^{2*}/S_{y_{a}}^{2}$
\end_inset

 is closer to 1 (Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:bias-1-1-1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, left).
 Considering that the true area values of untransformed welfare range from
 roughly 18 to 110, the bias for some areas is quite considerable.
 In accordance to what was noted in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec: method"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, the method yields unbiased values of the model's dependent variable, 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{y}_{a}$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 the transformed welfare (Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:bias-1-1-1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, right).
 This is a similar finding to that of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "chen2024effects"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 who through simulated illustrate that, in the presence of substantial model
 misspecifications, the unit context model shows similar performance to
 that of area-level models with known variances.
 Nevertheless, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "chen2024effects"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 do not provide results for the back-transformed variable.
 Considering that welfare usually requires transformation so that model
 assumptions are met, the author's results hold little value for international
 welfare and poverty monitoring.
\end_layout

